04 |isbn=978-962-209-651-6 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8IwcBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PP1 |quote= |via= |ref=harv |df= }}\n*{{Cite book|title=East Asian Film Noir: Transnational Encounters and Intercultural Dialogue |last=Shin |first=Chi-Yun |publisher=I.B.Tauris |date=2014 |isbn=978-1-78076-009-4 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T14TBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA167 |quote= |via= |ref=harv |df= }}\n*{{Cite book|title=Peter Ho-sun Chan's \"He's a Woman, She's a Man\" |last=Stokes |first=Lisa Odham |publisher=Hong Kong University Press |date=2009 |isbn=978-962-209-970-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sMDoj0v8KCYC&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2 |quote= |via= |ref=harv |df= }}\n*{{Cite book|title=Director in Action: Johnnie To and the Hong Kong Action Film |last=Teo |first=Stephen |publisher=Hong Kong University Press |date=2007 |isbn=978-962-209-839-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ma_UAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA104&lpg=PA104 |quote= |via= |ref=harv |df= }}\n*{{Cite book|title=The Modern Amazons: Warrior Women On-Screen |last=Ursini |first=James |publisher=Limelight Editions |date=2006 |isbn=978-0-87910-327-9 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AlKW5X7vccgC&pg=PA373 |quote= |via= |ref=harv |df= }}\n*{{Cite book|title=Encyclopedia of Chinese Film |last=Xiao |first=Zhiwei |publisher=Taylor & Francis Ebooks |date=2002 |isbn=978-1-134-74554-8 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XAeGAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA110 |quote= |via= |ref=harv |df= }}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=amqzDMOzaCUC&pg=PA242&lpg=PA242 |title=Once Upon a Time in China |last=Yang |first=Jeff |publisher=James Bennett Pty Ltd |date=2003 |isbn=978-0-7434-4817-8 |location= |quote= |via= |ref=harv |df= }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160830234550/http://www.hkfaa.com/ Hong Kong Film Awards Official Site]\n\n{{Best Actress HKFA}}\n{{Hong Kong Film Awards Chron}}\n\n{{featured list}}\n\n[[Category:Film awards for lead actress]]\n[[Category:Awards established in 1982]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong Film Awards]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox award\n| name        = '''[[Hong Kong Film Award]] for Best Actress'''\n| description = Best Performance by an Actress in a leading role\n| presenter   = [[Hong Kong Film Award]]s\n| country     = [[Hong Kong]]\n| year        = 1982 (for performances in films released in [[List of Hong Kong films of 1981|1981]]/[[List of Hong Kong films of 1982|1982]])\n| holder      = [[Chloe Maayan]] <br> ''[[Three Husbands (2018 film)|Three Husbands]]'' ([[38th Hong Kong Film Awards|2019]])\n| website     = {{url|hkfaa.com}}\n}}\nThe '''Hong Kong Film Award for Best Actress''' is an award presented annually at the [[Hong Kong Film Award]]s (HKFA). It is given to honour an actress who has delivered an outstanding performance in a [[Cinema of Hong Kong|Hong Kong film]].{{ref label|id1|Note 1|none}} The [[1st Hong Kong Film Awards]] ceremony was held in 1982, with no formal nomination procedure established; the award was given to [[Kara Hui]] for her role in ''[[My Young Auntie]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsdesk.si.edu/releases/international-screen-star-kara-wai-headline-2016-made-hong-kong-film-festival |title=International Screen Star Kara Wai To Headline 2016 Made in Hong Kong Film Festival |last= |first= |date=14 July 2016 |website= |publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]] |access-date=26 November 2016 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161127023559/http://newsdesk.si.edu/releases/international-screen-star-kara-wai-headline-2016-made-hong-kong-film-festival |archivedate=27 November 2016 |df= }}</ref> After the first award ceremony, a nomination system was put in place whereby no more than five nominations are made for each category and each entry is selected through two rounds of voting. Firstly, prospective nominees are marked with a weight of 50% each from HKFA voters and a hundred professional adjudicators, contributing towards a final score with which the top five nominees advance to the second round of voting. The winner is then selected via a scoring process where 55% of the vote comes from 55 professional adjudicators, 25% from representatives of the [[Hong Kong Performing Artistes Guild]] and 20% from all other HKFA Executive Committee Members.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\n[[Maggie Cheung]] holds the title of the most awards received having been honoured on five separate occasions. [[Sylvia Chang]] holds the record for the most nominated actress with ten nominations. Since its inception, 81 actresses have been nominated for the award with 26 actresses winning at least one of the 36 awards. \n\n==Winners and nominees==\nIn the following table award nominees are listed by year corresponding to the Hong Kong Film Awards' annual presentation ceremony. At the first incarnation of the ceremony in 1982 awards were presented to winners with no nominees selected. Thereafter, the winner is chosen from a list of nominees from the chosen category.\n[[File:SI Twenty-First Annual Made in Hong Kong Film Festival 01 Cropped.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Kara Hui]] was the first to win the award for her role in ''[[My Young Auntie]]'' (1981).|alt=Photo of Kara Hui at the world premiere of the Hong Kong film Happiness in 2015.]]\n\n[[File:Maggie Cheung cropped.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Maggie Cheung]] won the award five times for her roles in  A ''[[A Fishy Story|Fishy Story]]'' (1989), ''[[Center Stage (1991 film)|Center Stage]]'' (1991), ''[[Comrades: Almost a Love Story]]'' (1996), ''[[The Soong Sisters (film)|The Soong Sisters]]'' (1997) and ''[[In the Mood for Love]]'' (2000).|alt=Photo of Maggie Cheung at Shanghai movie festival in 2007.]]\n\n[[File:Brigitte lin ching hsia.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Brigitte Lin]] was nominated  for her role in ''[[Zu Warriors from the Magic Mountain]]'' as well as on three other occasions.|alt=Photo of Brigitte at the 2008 Dubai International Film Festival.]]\n\n[[File:Sandra Ng (cropped).jpg|thumb|120px|[[Sandra Ng]] won in 1998 for ''[[Portland Street Blues]]''.|alt=Photo of Sandra Ng in Bangkok 2007.]]\n\n[[File:Faye Wong.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Faye Wong]] was nominated for her roles in ''[[Chungking Express]]'' (1995) and ''[[Chinese Odyssey 2002]]''.|alt=Photo of Faye Wong in Kuala Lumpur 2011.]]\n\n[[File:Sylvia Chang 2011 (cropped).jpg|thumb|120px|[[Sylvia Chang]] won in 2002 for ''[[Forever and Ever (2001 film)|Forever and Ever]]''.|alt=Photo of Sylvia Chang at Hong Kong International Film Festival 2011.]]\n\n[[File:Cecilia Cheung 2012.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Cecilia Cheung]] won in 2004 for ''[[Lost in Time (film)|Lost in Time]]''.|alt=Photo of Cecilia Cheung in 2012.]]\n\n[[File:Zhang Ziyi Cabourg 2014 2.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Zhang Ziyi]] won in 2005 for ''[[2046 (film)|2046]]'' and in 2014 for ''[[The Grandmaster (film)|The Grandmaster]]''.|alt=Photo of Zhang ziyi at Cabourg Film Festival in 2014.]]\n\n[[File:Zhou Xun (cropped).jpg|thumb|120px|[[Zhou Xun]] won in 2006 for ''[[Perhaps Love (2005 film)|Perhaps Love]]''.|alt=Photo of Zhou Xun at CCTV-MTV music award ceremony in Beijing in July 2002.]]\n\n[[File:2007TaipeiITMonth KarenMok.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Karen Mok]] was nominated for her roles in ''[[The God of Cookery]]'' (1997) and ''[[Wait 'til You're Older]]'' (2006).|alt=Photo of Faye Wong in Kuala Lumpur 2011.]]\n\n[[File:Teresa Mo (cropped).jpg|thumb|120px|[[Teresa Mo]] was nominated in 2007 for ''Men Suddenly in Black 2'' and 2008 for ''[[Mr. Cinema]]''.|alt=Photo of Teresa Mo in 2011.]]\n\n[[File:Gong Li Cannes 2011.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Gong Li]] won in 2008 for ''[[Curse of the Golden Flower]]''.|alt=Photo of Gong Li at Cannes Film Festival in 2011.]]\n\n[[File:Shu Qi Cannes 2015.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Shu Qi]] was nominated for the award in both 2010 and 2012.|alt=Photo of Shu Qi at the 2015 Cannes Film Festival.]]\n\n[[File:Art Life 2013 1211 IMG 3605.JPG|thumb|120px|[[Gao Yuanyuan]] was nominated in 2012 for her role in [[Don't Go Breaking My Heart (2011 film)|''Don't Go Breaking My Heart'']]|alt=Photo of Gao Yuanyuan in Seoul 2011.]]\n\n[[File:Deanie YIP Tak-Han Mar-2013 (cropped).JPG|thumb|120px|[[Deanie Ip]] won in 2012 for ''[[A Simple Life]]''.|alt=Photo of Karen Mok in Taipei 2007.]]\n\n[[File:MiriamYeung2007-2 (cropped).jpg|thumb|120px|[[Miriam Yeung]] won in 2013 for ''[[Love in the Buff]]''.|alt=Photo of Miriam Yeung at SINA Music 2006.]]\n\n[[File:Zhaoweiredcarpet.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Zhao Wei]] won in 2015 for her role in ''[[Dearest (2014 film)|Dearest]]''.|alt=Photo of Zhao Wei at the Huabiao Awards in 2007.]]\n\n[[File:Tang Wei in Seoul 2011.jpg|thumb|120px|[[Tang Wei]] was nominated in 2016 for her role in ''[[A Tale of Three Cities]]''|alt=Photo of Gao Yuanyuan at China the art of life,11 December 2013.]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Table key\n|-\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86; height:20px; width:20px; text-align: center\"|{{double dagger|alt=Award winner}}\n| Indicates the winner\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#bebebe\"\n!scop=col| Year\n!scop=col| Actor\n!scop=col| Film\n!scop=col| Character name\n!scop=col colspan=\"2\" class=\"unsortable\"|{{Abbr|Refs.|References}}\n|- \n| align=\"center\" | '''[[List of Hong Kong films of 1981|1981]]<br><small>[[1st Hong Kong Film Awards|(1st)]]</small>'''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |[[Kara Hui]] \u2021\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[My Young Auntie]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |Cheng Tai-Nan\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeout.com/hong-kong/film/kara-hui-on-humble-beginnings-and-40-years-in-the-film-industry |title=Kara Hui (\u60e0\u82f1\u7d05) on humble beginnings and 40 years in the film industry |last=Tam |first=Arther |date=3 March 2016 |website=[[Time Out (magazine)|Time Out]] |publisher= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215113905/https://www.timeout.com/hong-kong/film/kara-hui-on-humble-beginnings-and-40-years-in-the-film-industry |archive-date=15 February 2017 |url-status=live|access-date=2 February 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n| <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hkfaa.com/history/list_01.html |title=1st Hong Kong Film Awards |language=Chinese |publisher=[[Hong Kong Film Awards]] |access-date=2 February 2017 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206060641/http://www.hkfaa.com/history/list_01.html |archivedate= 6 February 2010 |df= }}</ref>\n|- \n| rowspan=\"5\" align=\"center\" |'''[[List of Hong Kong films of 1982|1982]]<br><small>[[2nd Hong Kong Film Awards|(2nd)]]</small>'''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |[[Becky Lam]] \u2021 \n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |''[[Lonely Fifteen]]''\n| style=\"background:#FAEB86\" |Bik-Kei Lam\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hkcinemagic.com/en/movie.asp?id=2109 |title=Lonely Fifteen (1982) |last= |first= |date= |website= |publisher=[[Hong Kong Cinemagic]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160306212441/http://www.hkcinemagic.com/en/movie.asp?id=2109 |archive-date= 6 March 2016 |url-status=live|access-date=5 May 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n| rowspan=\"5\" | <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hkfaa.com/history/list_02.html |title=2nd Hong Kong Film Awards |language=Chinese |publisher=[[Hong Kong Film Awards]] |access-date=2 February 2017 |url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924030638/http://www.hkfaa.com/history/list_02.html |archivedate=24 September 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n|- \n|[[Cherie Chung]]\n|''Eclipse''\n|Fu Min\n|{{sfn|Kam|2016|p=24}}\n|-\n|[[Season Ma]]\n|''[[Boat People (film)|Boat People]]''\n|Cam Nuong\n|<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/27/movies/film-festival-vietnam-s-boat-people.html |title=Film Festival; Vietnam's 'Boat People' |last=Maslin |first=Janet |date=27 September 1983 |website=[[The New York Times]] |publisher= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215023646/http://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/27/movies/film-festival-vietnam-s-boat-people.html |archive-date=15 February 2017 |url-status=live|access-date=2 February 2017 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Cora Miao]]\n|''[[Boat People (film)|Boat People]]''\n|Nguyen's Mistress\